snippet.textDisplay: So proud! As a mom of a trans daughter, I hope you are able to use your platform to fight for rights of trans kids. Like your mom, by age 3 I thought my kid would be gay. My daughter was telling me kindly that she was present, until she was 7 and starting arguments in Walmart with her dad and screaming and crying to me that she was a girl. 3 years later and it’s still scary for me, so I can’t imagine how scary all of it is for her. Stay true🥰🥰🥰 I hope you see this and know that you are setting way for little trans girls to be visible and to be proud!

snippet.textDisplay: So I respect this coming out a lot, but to me, not telling your fiancé for YEARS that you’re trans is kind of fucked up. Here’s how i see it, if someone truly loves you they will be accepting, and if u hide it from someone out of fear you’ll never know if they really do. Also, some people are accepting of trans people but might not be sexually comfortable with it and that is okay. People who aren’t comfortable having sex with trans people shouldn’t be shamed for that, they just prefer their comfort zone and that’s fine. It’s not fair to them to continue a relationship with a woman believing you’ve always been a woman and falling in love and then dropping that bomb. I agree if you’re really in love it won’t matter, but again how will you know it’s rea until you say it? Say it on the first date and weed out the people who aren’t there yet and it makes life easier. I just don’t think this is cool, and I’m a very progressive accepting person, but your partner deserves to know this
